  <div class="about sec">
    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>The Viking Ship Museum (Vikingskipshuset) at Huk Aveny 35 on the Bygdøy Peninsula has been closed since September 2021 for complete rebuilding. The existing building, constructed in 1926, was no longer structurally or environmentally suitable for long-term preservation of the ships. The new building — the Museum of the Viking Age (Vikingtidsmuseet) — is under construction at the same site and is scheduled to open in 2027. The museum's three principal exhibits are the Oseberg ship, the Gokstad ship, and the Tune ship — the world's best-preserved Viking Age vessels, all excavated from burial mounds around the Oslofjord in the 19th and early 20th centuries.</p>
    <p>All three ships were physically relocated from the old museum building into the new Museum of the Viking Age during 2025–2026. The Tune ship completed its transfer in February 2026, and as of 25 February 2026 all three ships are confirmed safely installed in the new building. The Oseberg burial sledges — the most fragile objects in the collection — began their relocation in March 2026. The collection also includes wooden carts, textiles, tent equipment, and household items buried with the ships.</p>
    <p>During the construction period, Viking Age objects from the museum's collection are on display at the Historical Museum (Historisk museum) at Frederiks gate 2 in central Oslo, operated by the same institution (Museum of Cultural History, University of Oslo). The Historical Museum is a 10-minute walk from Oslo Central Station. Updates on the new museum are published at vikingtidsmuseet.no.<br/><em style="font-size:.68rem;color:var(--dim)">Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</em></p>
